        "# Module 2 — The Trapezoidal Rule and Approximating Areas with Application to Probability\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Error Function (erf) as Probability\n",
        "\n",
        "In probability, the **Normal distribution** is one of the most important models in science and engineering. This is also known as a **bell curve** or **Gaussian distribution**. You may have heard about bell curves when teachers think about grade distributions or perhaps in thinking about other population information (e.g. heights of people, etc.) Another context is the understanding of *errors* due to measurements, where you might assume measurements are close to the actual value, but with some small error (+/-).\n",
        "\n",
        "If a random variable or measurement \\(Z\\) is **standard normal**, then the probability that \\(Z\\) is between two numbers is an *area under the curve*:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "P(a \\le Z \\le b)=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi}}\\int_a^b e^{-s^2/2}\\,ds.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The issue we worked with in Mini-Project 2 was that $\\int e^{-x^2}\\,dx$ does **not** have an elementary antiderivative. This is related to the **error function**:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\operatorname{erf}(x)=\\frac{2}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\int_0^x e^{-t^2}\\,dt.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "**Question 2a.** What $u$-substitution would enable you to find a relationship between the two integrals below?\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi}}\\int_a^b e^{-s^2/2}\\,ds.\n",
        "$$,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\frac{2}{\\sqrt{\\pi}}\\int_0^x e^{-t^2}\\,dt.\n",
        "$$\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "SQ3YJ4GoJK4i"
      },
      "id": "SQ3YJ4GoJK4i"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
