        "Now let's explore why this definition of $$\n",
        "P(a \\le Z \\le b)=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi}}\\int_a^b e^{-s^2/2}\\,ds\n",
        "$$\n",
        "makes sense as a *probability*. There are a few features related to probability and our understanding of bell curves that we could test:\n",
        "\n",
        "- $P(a\\le Z \\le b)>0$: this condition is required for $P$ to represent probability (for any choice of $a$ or $b$).\n",
        "- $P(-\\infty \\le Z \\le \\infty)=1$: this condition is required for $P$ to represent probability.\n",
        "- $P(0\\le Z \\le \\infty)=0.5$: this condition is required for the symmetry of the bell curve."
