        "## Modeling Probabilities\n",
        "\n",
        "In Mini-Project 2, we introduced the idea that of prime factors. We called the events $A$ and $B$:\n",
        "\n",
        "- $A$ : $a$ has a prime factor of 2\n",
        "- $B$ : $b$ has a prime factor of 2\n",
        "\n",
        "Then, we said that\n",
        "$$P(A)= P(B) = \\frac{1}{2}$$\n",
        "which follows simply because half of all numbers are even (so must have a prime factor of 2).\n",
        "\n",
        "Consider the following scenario: suppose we randomly generate 100 numbers. On average, we would expect about 50 of these numbers to be even (or have prime factors of 2). However, we might ask ourselves what the likelihood is that more than 60 of them would be even, just by pure chance?\n",
        "\n",
        "Another way of thinking about this problem is as a coin toss. Out of 100 coin tosses, what is the likelihood (or probability) that 60 or more of them are heads? To understand this, we can *simulate* what might happen with 100 coin toses, but simulate this MANY times to estimate likelihoods of a variety of outcomes (e.g. 70 heads, 29 heads, etc.).\n",
        "\n",
        "**TASK.** Run the code below to simulate 100 coin tosses, 10000 times."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Parameters for the simulation\n",
        "num_tosses = 100  # Number of coin tosses per simulation\n",
        "prob_heads = 1/2  # Probability of getting heads/even number\n",
        "num_simulations = 10000 # N times the simulation is run (EDIT THIS PARAMETER if needed)\n",
        "avgHeadsExpected = prob_heads * num_tosses\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Simulate the binomial distribution\n",
        "# Each entry in 'results' will be the number of heads in 100 tosses\n",
        "results = np.random.binomial(num_tosses, prob_heads, num_simulations)\n",
        "results = results\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plotting the histogram\n",
