    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "It turns out that events like this where there are 2 possible outcomes (even and not even or heads and not heads) follow bell-shaped distributions. This is known as the **Central Limit Theorem** in statistics, but really means that if we want to understand problems like this, we can use the **normal distribution** or **bell curve** to estimate these probabilities, instead of simulating 10000 different scenarios to estimate the probabilities.\n",
        "\n",
        "This does require a little bit of re-scaling of our standard normal distribution:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "P(a \\le Z \\le b)=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi}}\\int_a^b e^{-s^2/2}\\,ds =\\frac{1}{S\\sqrt{2\\pi}}\\int_a^b e^{-(u-m)^2/(2S^2)}\\,du.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n"
      ],
