      "source": [
        "----\n",
        "\n",
        "# Module 3 — Infinite Summations (a.k.a. Series) with Applications to Relative Primeness and Probabilities\n",
        "<center><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jusimons/MATH19B/refs/heads/main/relative_primeness_circle.png\"/></center>\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "In this module of the prior mini-projects, we introduced the idea of **prime factorization** which is a way of expressing any integer as a product of its prime factors.\n",
        "\n",
        "Our goal was to find\n",
        "\n",
        "$$P(a,b\\text{ relatively prime})$$\n",
        "\n",
        "To remind you of where we are at, we will go a bit in reverse of our prior work. We found:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{align*}\n",
        "P(a,b\\text{ relatively prime})\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\bigg( 1 -\\frac{1}{2^2}\\bigg)\\bigg(1 -\\frac{1}{3^2}\\bigg)\\cdots \\\\\n",
        "&= \\prod_{p\\text{ is prime}} \\bigg( 1 -\\frac{1}{p^2}\\bigg)\n",
        "\\end{align*}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "Noting that if we take the reciprocal of expressions like\n",
        "$$\\bigg( 1 -\\frac{1}{p^2}\\bigg)$$\n",
        "we get:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\frac{1}{1 -\\frac{1}{p^2}}$$\n",
        "which reminds us of the geometric series formula:\n",
        "\n",
        " $$\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty r^n=\\frac{1}{1-r}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $r=\\frac{1}{p^2}$. This suggests that we could rewrite what we are looking for with summations:\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{align*}\n",
        "\\frac{1}{P(a,b\\text{ relatively prime})}\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\frac{1}{ 1 -\\frac{1}{2^2}}\\frac{1}{1 -\\frac{1}{3^2}}\\cdots \\\\\n",
        "&= \\prod_{p\\text{ is prime}} \\frac{1}{ 1 -\\frac{1}{p^2}}\n",
        "\\end{align*}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "We can then take this last part and rewrite the product using summations:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{align*}\n",
        "\\frac{1}{P(a,b\\text{ relatively prime})}\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\bigg(\\frac{1}{2^2}\\bigg)^n \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\bigg(\\frac{1}{3^2}\\bigg)^n\\cdots \\\\\n",
        "&= \\prod_{p\\text{ is prime}} \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\bigg(\\frac{1}{p^2}\\bigg)^n\n",
        "\\end{align*}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "We made the following claim:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\bigg(\\frac{1}{2^2}\\bigg)^n \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\bigg(\\frac{1}{3^2}\\bigg)^n=\\sum_{k,m=0}^\\infty \\frac{1}{(2^k3^m)^2}=\\sum \\frac{1}{n^2}$$\n",
        "for all $n$ whose prime factorization only contains 2 or 3.\n",
        "\n",
        "We now go one step further to claim that we should be able to do the same thourgh process for larger primes such as 5, 7, 11, ....\n",
        "\n",
        "In other words,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{align*}\n",
        "\\frac{1}{P(a,b\\text{ relatively prime})}\n",
        "&=\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\bigg(\\frac{1}{2^2}\\bigg)^n \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\bigg(\\frac{1}{3^2}\\bigg)^n\\cdots \\\\\n",
        "&= \\prod_{p\\text{ is prime}} \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\bigg(\\frac{1}{p^2}\\bigg)^n\\\\\n",
        "&=\\sum_{k,m,n,...=0}^\\infty \\frac{1}{(2^k3^m5^n \\cdots)^2}\\\\\n",
        "&=\\sum \\frac{1}{n^2}\n",
        "\\end{align*}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "for all $n$ (for any prime factorization numbers 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, ....)\n",
        "\n",
        "This is key because it turns our last summation into a more simple summation of just\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty \\frac{1}{n^2}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "with *no restriction on $n$*.\n",
        "\n",
        "There are a couple of ways to resolve this final summation, which actually has an *exact, finite* answer.\n",
        "\n",
        "But first, let's verify our claim that :\n",
        "$$\\prod_{p\\text{ is prime}} \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\bigg(\\frac{1}{p^2}\\bigg)^n = \\sum_{n=1}^\\infty \\frac{1}{n^2}$$\n",
        "by approximating both sides of this equation.\n",
        "\n",
        "**TASK.** Run the code below to compute $\\prod_{p\\text{ is prime}} \\sum_{n=0}^N \\bigg(\\frac{1}{p^2}\\bigg)^n$ for large $N$."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "29f7d6e5",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "29f7d6e5"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# To find primes:\n",
        "def sieve_primes(n):\n",
        "    if n < 2:\n",
        "        return []\n",
        "    is_prime = np.ones(n+1, dtype=bool)\n",
        "    is_prime[:2] = False\n",
        "    for p in range(2, int(n**0.5)+1):\n",
        "        if is_prime[p]:\n",
        "            is_prime[p*p:n+1:p] = False\n",
        "    return [i for i in range(2, n+1) if is_prime[i]]\n",
        "\n",
        "# To compute product:\n",
        "def partial_product(prime_max,N):\n",
        "    primes = sieve_primes(prime_max)\n",
        "    prod = 1.0\n",
        "    for p in primes:\n",
        "        sump2 = 0;\n",
        "        for n in range(0,N):\n",
        "          sump2 += (1.0/(p*p))**n\n",
        "        prod *= sump2\n",
        "    return prod\n",
        "\n",
        "# EDIT HERE: you can change the value of prime_max, N\n",
        "prime_max = 3\n",
        "N=10\n",
        "\n",
        "prod = partial_product(prime_max,N)\n",
        "print('Partial product for primes p up to', prime_max, ' and N = ', N, ' is: ', prod)\n"
      ]
    },
