        "# Module 4 — Approximations of Functions: Fourier Series and the Gibbs Phenomenon\n",
        "\n",
        "<center>\n",
        "  <img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jusimons/MATH19B/refs/heads/main/Synthesis_square.gif\" alt=\"Fourier Series animation for a step function, showing Gibbs phenomenon.\"/>\n",
        "</center>\n",
        "\n",
        "In Mini-Project 1, we introduced the idea of Fourier Series and asked you to compute a Fourier Series for a particular function ($f(x) = 2$). In Mini-Project 2, we extended this to another function ($f(x)=x^2$) and introduced the idea of *othogonality*.\n",
        "\n",
        "Now we will extend this in two ways:\n",
        "1. Computing an interesting series;\n",
        "2. To explore fundamental features of the *Gibbs Phenomenon* through understanding *error*.\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "VORd75zEGtWy",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "VORd75zEGtWy"
      },
      "source": [
        "## An interesting series\n",
        "\n",
        "You have already shown that the Fourier series for\n",
        "$f(x) = x^2$ on -$\\pi < x < \\pi$\n",
        "is given by\n",
        "$$\\frac{\\pi^2}{3}+4\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty \\frac{(-1)^n}{n^2}\\cos(nx)$$\n",
        "This means\n",
        "$$x^2= \\frac{\\pi^2}{3}+4\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty \\frac{(-1)^n}{n^2}\\cos(nx)$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Notice that this is an *exact* equation--we have to prove this, but in general it is true that Fourier series are exactly equal to the function that generates the series.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Question 4a.** Plug in $x=\\pi$ to compute the value of $$\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty \\frac{1}{n^2}$$ *exactly*."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "a0rPsXXyFJR8",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "a0rPsXXyFJR8"
      },
      "source": [
